      "role": "user",
      "content": "Hey, can you help me understand the difference between a \"confidentiality period\" and a \"survival clause\" in a standard contract? I'm trying to make sure I don't miss anything important.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Of course! A confidentiality period in a contract is a time frame during which you, the party receiving the information, are expected to keep certain details secret. It's like a secret handshake between you and the other party, where you promise not to share the secret recipes of the best chocolate cake ever made by the local bakery. On the other hand, a survival clause is a bit like a protective spell that keeps the contract alive even if some parts of it become irrelevant or are removed. Imagine you have a magical shield that protects your treasure chest from being stolen, even if the map to the treasure is lost. So, while the confidentiality period is about keeping secrets, the survival clause is about keeping the contract's magic alive.",
